before and after:

tokens_with_stop <- pubmed %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  count(term, word, sort = TRUE)

data("stop_words")
tokens_no_stop <- pubmed %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word") %>%
  count(term, word, sort = TRUE)
top5_with_stop <- tokens_with_stop %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  slice_max(order_by = n, n = 5) %>%
  summarise(Top_Words_Before = paste(word, collapse = ", "))

top5_no_stop <- tokens_no_stop %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  slice_max(order_by = n, n = 5) %>%
  summarise(Top_Words_After = paste(word, collapse = ", "))

comparison_table <- left_join(top5_with_stop, top5_no_stop, by = "term") %>%
  rename(Search_Term = term)

kable(comparison_table,
      caption = "Comparison of Top 5 Tokens Before vs After Removing Stop Words",
      align = c("l", "l", "l"),
      col.names = c("Search Term", "Top 5 Tokens (Before)", "Top 5 Tokens (After)")) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE, bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed")) %>%
  row_spec(0, bold = TRUE, color = "white", background = "#2e8b57") %>%
  column_spec(1:3, background = "#e9f7ef")
Comparison of Top 5 Tokens Before vs After Removing Stop Words
Search Term Top 5 Tokens (Before) Top 5 Tokens (After)
covid the, of, covid, 19, and covid, 19, patients, disease, pandemic
cystic fibrosis the, of, and, in, to fibrosis, cystic, cf, patients, disease
meningitis the, of, and, in, a patients, meningitis, meningeal, csf, clinical
preeclampsia the, of, and, in, to pre, eclampsia, preeclampsia, women, pregnancy
prostate cancer the, of, and, cancer, prostate cancer, prostate, patients, treatment, disease 
tokens_with_stop$condition <- "Before"
tokens_no_stop$condition <- "After"

combined_tokens <- bind_rows(tokens_with_stop, tokens_no_stop)

top_tokens <- combined_tokens %>%
  group_by(term, condition) %>%
  slice_max(order_by = n, n = 5)

ggplot(top_tokens, aes(x = reorder_within(word, n, term), y = n, fill = condition)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge", width = 0.7) +
  facet_wrap(~term, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_x_reordered() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Before" = "#6fbf73", "After" = "#1b5e20")) +
  labs(
    title = "Top 5 Tokens Before vs After Removing Stop Words",
    x = "Token",
    y = "Frequency",
    fill = "Condition"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 13) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14),
    axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
    legend.position = "bottom"
  )

Before eliminating stop words, the most frequent tokens were general English terms like the, and, and of, which provide little analytical value in biomedical text mining. Once stop words were removed, the top tokens reflected domain-specific and meaningful biological concepts â for instance, âcovidâ and âpatientsâ in COVID-19 studies, âcancerâ and âprostateâ in prostate cancer research, and âpreeclampsiaâ and âpregnancyâ in maternal health topics. This demonstrates that removing stop words substantially enhances the clarity and relevance of token frequency analyses.

data("stop_words")

tidy_pubmed <- pubmed %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word") %>%
  filter(!is.na(word))
word_counts <- tidy_pubmed %>%
  count(term, word, sort = TRUE)
tfidf <- word_counts %>%
  bind_tf_idf(word, term, n) %>%
  arrange(desc(tf_idf))

  group_by(term) %>%

ggplot(top5_tfidf, aes(x = reorder_within(word, tf_idf, term),
                       y = tf_idf, fill = term)) +

  coord_flip() +

  labs(

    x = NULL,
    y = "TF-IDF Score"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 15) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 20, hjust = 0.5),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 13, hjust = 0.5, color = "gray35"),
    axis.title.x = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14),
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 12),
    strip.text = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
    panel.spacing = unit(1.5, "lines"),
    plot.margin = margin(15, 30, 15, 15),
    panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  ) +
  expand_limits(y = max(top5_tfidf$tf_idf) * 1.15)

TF-IDF identifies words that are unique to each search term, not just frequent overall. In Question 1, the top tokens were generic, high-frequency words within each topic (âcovid,â âcancer,â âpreeclampsiaâ). Now, the top TF-IDF words are more specific and distinctive, e.g.:âsars,â âpandemic,â âspikeâ for COVID âandrogen,â âpsa,â âptenâ for prostate cancer âplacenta,â âhypertension,â âmaternalâ for preeclampsia Therefore: TF-IDF shifts focus from common topic words to terms that best characterize the unique vocabulary of each search group â making the analysis more discriminative and informative.

When all sentiments are included, positive and negative dominate, reflecting the evaluative nature of biomedical writing. After excluding these general categories, distinct patterns emerge: COVID-19 abstracts show fear linked to uncertainty, prostate cancer studies emphasize trust reflecting scientific confidence, and preeclampsia papers express sadness related to maternal complications. Removing âpositiveâ and ânegativeâ highlights emotion-specific trends that better capture each topicâs tone.

  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word")

  inner_join(afinn, by = "word")

abstract_scores <- sentiment_afinn %>%
  group_by(term, abstract_id) %>%
  summarise(mean_sentiment = mean(value, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup()

COVID-19 and preeclampsia abstracts tend to have more negative sentiment, possibly reflecting the public health risks and adverse outcomes discussed in these studies.
